There are two avenues to blocking No Deal Brexit, the first is to bring down the government and the second is to force the government to seek an extension. The first avenue is itself blocked: the opposition and those MPs willing to align themselves with the opposition, cannot coalesce behind any leader: Corbyn is unacceptable and will not stand down, and the SNP & LibDems are too small, and there is a question about having the SNP lead the government of the United Kingdom when its goal is to leave it. Legally, a vote of no confidence would not immediately result in a general election and so the only way to force a rapid change of government would be to vote on an early day motion (EDM), which would be a vote of confidence in a specific individual, and so we get back to the leadership question the opposition has. The Benn Act, then, to my mind, is the last stand against No Deal. I have looked at John Major's notion that the government could get round the Benn Act through an order in council, but i think the whole business unlikely and even the government has dismissed the idea -which could be through sand in our eyes, but to what end? There are a few loopholes in the Benn Act: if parliament agrees to a deal, then the government is absolved of its responsibility to send a letter requesting an extension. The other loophole is that the Prime Minister must accept an extension according to the parameters detailed in his letter, which requests an extension till January 31 2020. In other words, if the European Council proposed an extension outside of this date, the Prime Minister need not accept the extension. More on this here: https://ukconstitutionallaw.org/2019/09/13/oliver-garner-the-benn-burt-extension-act-a-roadblock-to-a-no-deal-brexit/. There is the possibility of some nation, like Hungary, vetoing an extension request, but judging by Juncker and Varadkar's statements, this is extremely unlikely considering the nations most affected by Brexit -France, Germany, etc- have little incentive to veto an extension, this would imply a country like Hungary acting against the interests of France and Germany... The government could simply throw its toys out of the pram and veto key decisions and make itself such a nuisance the EU vetoes an extension request, but with only a week left, that would be quite a tantrum. Finally, civil servants are obliged to follow the law and if they perceive the government to be breaking the law, they may simply not co-operate in enforcing its will. All this rambling leads me to think that the Prime Minister is attempting to drive a bus through the eye of a needle. There is a gulf between rhetoric and reality and I keep asking myself: if Boris Johnson could get round the Benn Act, why has he not announced how he will do it? In 2019, leaks are inevitable, and yet, nothing... Boris Johnson cannot remain Prime Minister, uphold the law and exit on 31 Oct. 2019.
